Projected estimates for global warming are expected to pose serious challenges for existing systems of grain production around the globe, with some regions having predicted decreases in production as high as 70% (
 
  1
 ). Understanding how farmers coped with past changes in the mean state of climate may be crucial for understanding how we must adapt to a rapidly changing world. Humans are able to tolerate varying levels of failure in their agricultural systems. But exactly how many years of a bad harvest were humans able to cope with before they modified their farming strategies? What type of strategies did they use when returns got bad?
